john.dehaven@wov.com (John Dehaven) writes:


> JW> A true 'random string' is an infinite string produced
> JW> by a random process... and infinite strings of this kind aren't
> JW> compressible.

>Yikes!  Does it really mean anything to speak about
>"compressing" infinite strings?  The only thing that makes any
>sense to me is given a finite algorithm that generates an
>infinite string, then that algorithm is a "compressed" form of
>the string, because it is finite.  Other than that, what,
>though???

It could.  If I process an infinite string that is produced at the rate 
of two megabytes per second so that it compresses to a rate of one 
megabyte per second, have I not compressed an infinite string (assuming I 
keep it up forever)?
